## Regulatory Requirements

### Federal Requirements

**FCC Registration:**
- Register through FCC Commission Registration System (CORES)
- Obtain FCC Registration Number (FRN)
- File FCC Form 499-A (annual) and Form 499-Q (quarterly)

> Source: [FCC](https://www.fcc.gov/general/information-firms-providing-telecommunications-services-0)

**Key Federal Compliance Areas:**
| Requirement | Description |
|-------------|-------------|
| **Section 214 Authority** | Required for interstate telecommunications |
| **Form 499-A Registration** | USAC registration, triggers USF obligations |
| **CALEA** | Law enforcement access requirements |
| **CPNI** | Customer Proprietary Network Information protection |
| **HAC Certification** | Hearing Aid Compatibility (Form 855) |

> Source: [CommLaw Group](https://commlawgroup.com/compliance-resources/wireless-regulatory-compliance-guide/)

### State Requirements

States cannot regulate wireless rates or market entry, BUT they can require:
- Registration before offering service
- E911 compliance
- Annual reporting
- Consumer complaint handling
- Universal service contributions

**Example - California:**
All CMRS providers and resellers must register with the California PUC before providing service.

> Source: [Bronston Legal](https://telecomlawyer.net/licenses/mvno-licensing/)

### E911 Compliance

**Key Requirements:**
- Transmit caller location to Public Safety Answering Points (PSAPs)
- Enable direct 911 dialing (no prefix required - Kari's Law)
- Provide dispatchable location including floor/suite (Ray Baum's Act)

**MVNO Responsibility:** MVNOs typically rely on host carrier's E911 infrastructure but must ensure compliance is maintained.

> Source: [FCC](https://www.fcc.gov/general/9-1-1-and-e9-1-1-services)

### Penalties for Non-Compliance

- FCC fines can reach **tens of thousands of dollars per violation**
- Service suspension possible
- In extreme cases, E911 failures can result in loss of life and massive liability

